    <div class="scrollblock block-1">
      <a href="https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit" class="openstack"></a>
        <h1>"A La Openstack" - the simple guide</h1>
        <p>A simple guide for getting started with developing like the Openstack project.</p>
        <img src="../tutorial_images/arrow.png" alt="">
    </div>
    <!-- intro -->
    <a name="intro"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-8">
        <h2>introduction</h2>
        <p>Throughout this tutorial, we'll walk you through the modification of a hello world Python tutorial.</p>
        <p>You will go hands on and modify the code before pushing it to GERRIT, see ZUUL and JENKINS pass your changes through a Python lint checker and approve for inclusion.</p>
    </div>
    <!-- setup -->
    <a name="setup"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-2">
        <h2>setup</h2>
        <p>
            <a href="http://git-scm.com/download/mac">Download git for OSX</a>
        </p>
        <p>
            <a href="http://git-scm.com/download/win">Download git for Windows</a>
        </p>
        <p>
            <a href="http://git-scm.com/download/linux">Download git for Linux</a>
        </p>
        <p>
              After downloading and installing git for your apropiate system open a git command line, this is where you'll mainly be working.<br>
              If you have difficulty installing git, for example on Ubuntu, make sure you have already added the repository:<br>
              ><code><p2>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:git-core/ppa</p2></code><br>
              ><code><p2>sudo apt-get update</p2></code><br>
              At this point you should be able to install git following the link above.
        </p>
           
    </div>
    <a name="sshconfig"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-3">
        <h2>Configure ssh</h2>
        <p>
            On Windows, download <a href="http://users.ugent.be/~bpuype/cgi-bin/fetch.pl?dl=wget/wget-1.10.2.exe">wget.exe</a> to your "Downloads" folder. Make sure that you replace each 'wget' below by '~/Downloads/wget'.<br>Start GIT bash.<br>
            &gt;<code><p2>mkdir .ssh</p2></code><br>
            When connected directly to the internet:<br>
        &gt;<code><p2>wget --no-check-certificate https://raw.githubusercontent.com/forj/tutorials/master/keys/demo_keys -O ~/.ssh/demo_keys</p2></code> <br>
      
      Or, behind a web proxy:<br>
        &gt;<code><p2>wget --no-check-certificate -e use_proxy=yes -e https_proxy=https://&lt;web-proxy&gt;:8080 https://raw.githubusercontent.com/forj/tutorials/master/keys/demo_keys -O ~/.ssh/demo_keys</p2> </code><br>
      You now have a "demo_keys" file in your home/.ssh directory ($HOME on Linux, %HOMEPATH% on Windows)<br>
      Let's modify the permissions of this file for linux systems:<br>
      ><code><p2>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/demo_keys</p2></code><br>
      Now let's install connect-proxy for linux systems:<br>
      ><code><p2>sudo apt-get install connect-proxy</p2></code><br>
        </p>
        <p>
            Create a "config" file with your favorite text editor (you might need to make hidden files visible)<br>
            ><code><p2>vi ~/.ssh/config</p2></code> for linux systems or <br>
            ><code><p2>notepad ~/.ssh/config</p2></code> for Windows systems and<br>
            add these lines to the "config" file (note that the file doesn't have an extension such as .txt)<br>
            <code><p2>Host <font color="33FF33">review</font></p2></code><br>
            <code><p2>  Hostname <%=gerrit_ip%></code><br/>
            <code><p2>  User demouser</p2></code><br>
            <code><p2>  Port 29418</p2></code><br>
            <code><p2>  identityfile ~/.ssh/demo_keys</p2></code><br>
            Add this line if you are behind a web proxy:<br>
            <code><p2>  ProxyCommand connect -H web-proxy:8080 %h %p</p2></code> replacing 'web-proxy:8080' with your proxy hostname and port.<br>
    </p></div>
    <a name="checkout"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-3">
        <h2>checkout the Tutorial repository</h2>
        <p>
            create a working copy of the Tutorial repository by running the command<br>
        &gt;<code><p2>git clone ssh://demouser@<font color="33FF33">review</font>:29418/tutorials.git</p2></code><br>
        </p>
        <p>
            This will download the code locally on the folder you are in you command line so that you can edit it.
        </p>
        <p>
            You actually get all the history and metadata of the code: this is great to work completely disconnected from the remote repository. Check by yourself:<br>
            Code history:<br>
            &gt;<code>
            <p2>cd  tutorials</p2></code><br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git log</p2></code><br>
            Details of a specific change:<br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git show 6687e07c859e2d3ff6136a5745d8932fe441a60a</p2></code>
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="gerrit"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-4">
        <h2>configure the repository to work with Gerrit</h2>
        <p>
            Our workflow requires code to be reviewed at several stages using Gerrit. Let's prepare to take advantage of Gerrit and commit to the
            <a href="https://review.openstack.org/Documentation/intro-quick.html#_creating_the_review">magic branch</a>:<br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git config remote.origin.push refs/heads/*:refs/for/*</p2></code><br>
            Install the commit hook which automatically generates unique Change-Ids in commit messages for Gerrit<br>
        &gt;<code><p2>wget --no-check-certificate https://<font color="33FF33"><%=gerrit_ip%></font>/tools/hooks/commit-msg -O .git/hooks/commit-msg</p2></code><br>
      If you are behind a proxy your command will be:<br>
      
        &gt;<code><p2>wget --no-check-certificate -e use_proxy=yes -e https_proxy=https://mywebproxy.com:8080  https://<font color="33FF33"><%=gerrit_ip%></font>/tools/hooks/commit-msg -O .git/hooks/commit-msg </p2></code><br>

      now run this command <br>
            &gt;<code><p2>chmod u+x .git/hooks/commit-msg</p2></code><br>
            now change the git user email <br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git config user.email "demouser@localhost"</p2></code><br>
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="modify"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-5">
        <h2>modify a file</h2>
        <p>
            modify the file at <br>
            <code>
            <p2>/path/to/repository/tutorials/openstack/helloworld.py</p2></code><br>
            and change any text you want.
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="add"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-6">
        <h2>add &amp; commit</h2>
        <p>List your changes with:<br>
            &gt;<code>
            <p2> git status</p2></code><br>
            now, add the changes in your local repository:<br>
            &gt;<code>
            <p2>git add openstack/helloworld.py</p2></code> or<br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git add *</p2></code><code><p2></p2></code><br>
            To actually commit, do:<br>
            &gt;<code>
            <p2>git commit -m "Changed text on helloworld.py"</p2></code><br>
            Now the file is committed to the <b>local</b> repository, but not in the <b>remote</b> repository yet.
      </p>
    </div>
    <a name="push"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-7">
        <h2>pushing changes</h2>
        <p>
            To send those changes to the remote repository, execute <br>
            &gt;<code><p2>git push</p2></code><br>
            The changes are now ready for review.
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="zuul"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-8">
        <h2>zuul: check pipeline</h2>
        <p>
            The change goes through Zuul's <i>check</i> pipeline which verifies automatically any change. If the check fails, the change is rejected.<br>
            Open Zuul interface to see the pipelines and the change as it goes through Zuul:<br>
            <a href="http://<%=zuul_ip%>/"><code><p2><font color="33FF33">http://<%=zuul_ip%></font></p2></code></a>
            
        </p>
        <img src="../tutorial_images/zuul.1.jpg" alt="">
        <p>
          As you can see, we have a python lint check:  using <a href="https://flake8.readthedocs.org/en/2.0/">Flake8</a>.
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="review"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-9">
        <h2>Review the change</h2>
        <p>
            Go to Gerrit to open your change:<br>
        <a href="https://<%=gerrit_ip%>//"><code><p2><font color="33FF33">https://<%=gerrit_ip%>/</font></p2></code></a><br>
            
            The change needs to be "Verified", "Code-Review" and "Approved" (the "Need" lines).<br>
            Verifying is checking that the code actually compiles, unit tests pass etc. Verification is done by Jenkins jobs configured in the "check" Zuul pipeline.<br>
            The check is automated and adds a +1 under "Verified".
        </p>
        <img src="../tutorial_images/gerrit.1.jpg" alt="">
    </div>
    <a name="merge"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-10">
        <h2>Submitting the change</h2>
        <p>
      As a reviewer, look at the code, comment it and make yourself an opinion about the change.<br>
      Now click on the <i>Review</i> button.<br>
      Voting +1 or -1 provides an opinion.<br>
      -2 rejects the change and +2 accepts it.<br>
        </p>
        <p>
          Go ahead: vote +2 for this example, add your comment and click on the "Publish and Submit". The code gets merged.
        </p>
    </div>
    <a name="gate"></a>
    <div class="scrollblock block-11">
        <h2>Zuul "gate" pipeline</h2>
        <p>
      Once a reviewer approved the changes, Zuul will make the change go through the <i>gate</i> pipeline.
        </p>
